n=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/12.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Which is safer? Flying chernobyls or big fireworks</span><hr size=1> <br>
yales, I will repeat: Prove it to me.  You have not cited a single source, and frankly I find your reasoning suspect.<br>
<br>
For example, you state with great drama the high enrichment levels of a nuclear boosters fuel, shortly after you state that the FISSION PRODUCTS are the source of the &quot;fallout.&quot;  Ergo, the level of enrichment has little impact (according to your own logic) on the level of &quot;fallout.&quot;<br>
<br>
(As a note,  where did you get that 90 percent enrichment figure?  I have seen many designs for nuclear boosters, and most use much lower enrichment levels than that.)<br>
<br>
You state: <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  A 2.5 million pound thrust nuclear engine (or cluster) runs at 45 gigawatts thermal and contains at equilibrium more than TWENTY times the fallout products. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
While this sounds very ominous, it is incorrect.  Like all good propaganda, it starts with a fact and then veers into untruth or half-truth.  Let me explain:<br>
<br>
What does the power density of the booster have to do with the fission fragments that are produced?  Power density governs (among other things) how quickly your fuel &quot;burns up.&quot;  IE, a nuclear reactor may reach burnup in ten years, while a booster reaches burnup in an hour.  Both will produce the same number of fission byproducts per unit mass of fuel.  The booster just gets there quicker.  Hopefully WAY quicker.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
For example:   <br>
<br>
A reactor has 100 kilos of fuel.  <br>
<br>
A booster also has 100 kilos of fuel.  <br>
<br>
In ten years, the reactor reaches 50 percent burnup, so there are 50 kilos or so of fission byproducts in the core.  <br>
<br>
In an hour, the booster reaches burnup of 50 percent, and amazingly enough, there are 50 kilos or so of fission byproducts in its core too.  <br>
<br>
(Please note, this is HUGELY simplifed.)  <br>
<br>
They may be different &quot;flavors&quot; of stuff, but the amounts will be the same.  In no WAY will there be &quot;20 times&quot; as much fission fragments in the booster core.  <br>
<br>
Now, I will note that they may have 20 times as much ACTIVITY, but activity is a very poor indicator of risk.  (I will provide a real-life example of this in data below, from Chernobyl, comparing Xenon to Cesium.)<br>
<br>
<br>
So, I ask again, detail for me the scenario where a nuclear powered booster can release 180,500 kilos of core material.  Since we are in more detail mode now, lay out for me the exact isotopes released.<br>
<br>
<br>
Oh, and your assertion that most of a reactor core's mass is &quot;heavy inert metal&quot; is also wrong in the case of an RBMK type reactor such as I carefully chose for my example.  Most of an RBMK core is composed of graphite.  Much of the release at Chernobyl occurred when the core CAUGHT FIRE and burned like a torch!  The smoke plume carried huge amounts of everything in the core and scattered it all over.  A Very Bad Scene.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    <br>
<br>
Repeat after me: Positive Void Co-Efficient is BAD. <br>
<br>
Oh, and as I thought was clear from the links I provided about the Chernobyl release, all of the &quot;fallout&quot; studied there was indeed FISSION PRODUCTS.  Please refer to the table in the linked page which details the release of 6500 petabecquerels of Xenon, etc.  The long-lasting stuff was essentially all Cesium in two isotopes, with 139 PBq released.  Note that the report states that the Cesium is FAR more dangerous than the xenon, despite the fact that there was much more activity of xenon released.  No mention of base fuel.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<br>
Facts, facts, facts.....  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
I will freely admit that this is a complicated topic, as it combines both nuclear engineering and rocket science, two famously difficult topics into one.  If anyone has any questions, or if I am unclear, or if heaven forbid I make a mistake, please ask me about it.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<br>
Well, I was going to post my thoughts on a nuclear powered heavy-lift booster, but I seem to be spending time debating the fine points of nuclear risk with yales.  But do not fear!  I will return after a refreshing sleep.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
